 areas\">Smoke Control Area.</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/preventing-air-pollution/dark-smoke","slug":"dark-smoke","order":2,"title":"Dark smoke","body":"<p>The darker the smoke, the more polluting it tends to be. Smoke darker than a specified shade of grey is officially classified as &lsquo;dark smoke&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>The <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://shop.bsigroup.com/en/ProductDetail/?pid=000000000000373338&amp;lang=_e\" title=\"Ringelmann chart\">Ringelmann chart</a> is used to define dark smoke. The chart has 5 shades of grey with 0 being clear and 5 being black. Smoke is considered &lsquo;dark&rsquo; if it is shade 2 or darker. </p>\n\n<h2>What you must do</h2>\n\n<p>You must not release dark smoke from your premises, including from: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>chimneys serving furnaces</li>\n  <li>fixed boilers or industrial plants, whether they&rsquo;re attached to buildings or not</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There are some exemptions if emissions won&rsquo;t damage health or cause a nuisance.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/preventing-air-pollution/boilers-and-furnaces","slug":"boilers-and-furnaces","order":3,"title":"Boilers and furnaces","body":"<p>Most generators, furnaces or boilers need a permit from the Environment Agency (or the Scottish Environment Protection Agency (<abbr title=\"Scottish Environment Protection Agency\">SEPA</abbr>) in Scotland), or your local council.</p>\n\n<h2>Get a permit</h2>\n<p>Contact the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/contactus/default.aspx\" title=\"Contact the Environment Agency\">Environmental Agency</a> or <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.sepa.org.uk/about_us/contacting_sepa/regional_offices.aspx\" title=\"Contact SEPA\"><abbr title=\"Scottish Environment Protection Agency\">SEPA</abbr></a> for a Part A(1) environmental permit if your appliances:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have an aggregated rated thermal input of 50 megawatts (<abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr>) or more</li>\n  <li>burn waste oil, recovered oil or any fuel made from waste, with a rated thermal input of 3 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr> to 50 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Contact your <a href=\"/find-your-local-council\" title=\"find your local council\">local council</a> for a Part B environmental permit if your appliances:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have a rated thermal input of 20 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr> to 50 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr></li>\n  <li>burn waste excluded from the Waste Incineration Directive (WID) with a rated thermal input of 0.4 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr> to 3 <abbr title=\"Megawatts\">mw</abbr></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Installing furnaces</h2>\n<p>Your local council must approve:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the use of a new non-domestic furnace in a building, fixed boiler or industrial plant</li>\n  <li>changes to an existing furnace</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Contact your local council about grit and dust arrestment if you don&rsquo;t have an environmental permit and your furnace is going to be used to burn:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>pulverised fuel</li>\n  <li>any other solid matter at a rate of 45.4 kilograms (<abbr title=\"Kilograms\">kg</abbr>) or more an hour</li>\n  <li>liquid or gaseous matter at a rate equivalent to 366.4 kilowatts (<abbr title=\"Kilowatts\">kw</abbr>) or more</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Chimney height requirements</h2>\n<p>Your chimney must be high enough to prevent smoke, grit, dust, gases and fume emissions from damaging health or causing a nuisance. Your local council can refuse your application if the chimney isn&rsquo;t high enough. </p>\n\n<p>You must apply for chimney height approval if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you don&rsquo;t have an environmental permit</li>\n  <li>your boiler&rsquo;s fuel consumption exceeds 45.4 <abbr title=\"Kilograms\">kg</abbr> of solid fuel per hour</li>\n  <li>your boiler&rsquo;s fuel consumption exceeds 366.4 <abbr title=\"Kilowatts\">kw</abbr> of liquid or gas fuel per hour</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your approval application is refused your local council will tell you the minimum chimney height you need.</p>\n\n<p>A chimney may be exempt if it is used as part of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a temporary replacement, for example if the boiler or furnace is being repaired</li>\n  <li>a temporary source of heat or power for building works</li>\n  <li>an auxiliary plant to bring the main plant up to operating temperatures</li>\n  <li>a mobile source of heat or power for agricultural purposes</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your use of the chimney changes you must re-apply for approval.</p>\n\n<h2>Boiler emission requirements</h2>\n<p>You must fit all boilers with grit and dust arrestment equipment. You can apply to your <a href=\"/find-your-local-council\" title=\"find your local council\">local council</a> for an exemption if the boiler will not create emissions that could damage health or cause a nuisance. </p>\n\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-11-06T15:49:01+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Waste and environmental impact","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Fwaste-environment.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes waste management plans, hazardous waste and preventing pollution","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Fwaste-environment","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/waste-environment"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Business Link","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/businesslink.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":null,"short_description":null,"t